{{Indigenous Peoples of Canada}}

'''Aboriginal peoples in [[Canada]]''' comprise the [[First Nations]],<ref name="First Nations Culture Areas Index">{{cite web
  | title = Civilization.ca-Gateway to Aboriginal Heritage-Culture
  | work = Canadian Museum of Civilization Corporation
  | publisher = Government of Canada
  | date = May 12, 2006
  | url = http://www.civilization.ca/cmc/exhibitions/tresors/ethno/etb0170e.shtml
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}</ref> [[Inuit]]<ref name="ICCcharter">{{cite web
  | title = Inuit Circumpolar Council (Canada)-ICC Charter
  | work = Inuit Circumpolar Council > ICC Charter and By-laws > ICC Charter
  | publisher = 
  | date = 2007
  | url = http://inuitcircumpolar.com/index.php?auto_slide=&ID=374&Lang=En&Parent_ID=&current_slide_num=
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}
</ref> and [[M<U+00E9>tis people (Canada)|M<U+00E9>tis]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = In the Kawaskimhon Aboriginal Moot Court  Factum of the Federal Crown Canada
  | work = Faculty of Law
  | publisher =[[University of Manitoba]]
  | date = 2007
  | url = http://www.umanitoba.ca/law/newsite/kawaskimhon_factums/FINALWrittenSubmissionsofFederalCrown_windsor.pdf
  | format = pdf
|page=2
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}
</ref> The descriptors Indian and [[Eskimo]] are falling into disuse.<ref name="kaplan"/>  [[Old Crow Flats]] and [[Bluefish Caves]] are the earliest archaeological sites of human habitation in Canada.<ref name=Griebel/>  The [[Paleo-Indian]] [[Clovis culture|Clovis]], [[Plano cultures]] and [[Pre-Dorset]] pre-date American indigenous and Inuit cultures.  [[Projectile point]] tools, [[spear]]s, [[pottery]], [[bangles]], [[chisels]] and [[Scraper (archaeology)|scrapers]] mark archaeological sites, thus distinguishing cultural periods and traditions.  

Hundreds of Aboriginal nations evolved trade, spiritual and [[social hierarchies]]. The M<U+00E9>tis culture of [[mixed blood]] originated in the mid-17th century when First Nation and native Inuit married European settlers.<ref name=testt/> The Inuit had more limited interaction with [[Europe|European]] settlers during that early period.<ref name=warin/> 

Various [[:Category:Canadian Aboriginal case law|laws]], [[treaties]], and legislation have been enacted between European immigrants and First Nations across Canada.  Aboriginal Right to [[Self-Government]] provides opportunity to manage historical, cultural, political, [[health care]] and economic control aspects within first people's communities.  

There are currently over 600 recognized [[List of First Nations peoples|First Nations governments or bands]] encompassing 1,172,790 <sup>2006</sup> peoples spread across Canada with distinctive Aboriginal cultures, languages, art, and music.<ref name="one">{{cite web
  | title = Assembly of First Nations&nbsp;-&nbsp;Assembly of First Nations-The Story
  | publisher = Assembly of First Nations
  | url = http://www.afn.ca/article.asp?id=59 
  | accessdate = 2009-10-02}}
</ref><ref name="three">{{cite web
  | title = Civilization.ca-Gateway to Aboriginal Heritage-object
  | publisher = Canadian Museum of Civilization Corporation
  | date = May 12, 2006
  | url = http://www.civilization.ca/cmc/exhibitions/tresors/ethno/etb0000e.shtml
  | accessdate = 2009-10-02}}
</ref><ref name="Aboriginal Identity 2006 Census"/>  [[National Aboriginal Day]] recognises the cultures and contributions of Aboriginal peoples of Canada.<ref name=history/>  In all walks of life First Nations, Inuit and M<U+00E9>tis peoples have become prominent figures serving as role models in the Aboriginal community and help to shape the Canadian cultural identity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naaf.ca/program/92|work=National Aboriginal Achievement Foundation|title=National Aboriginal Achievement Award Recipients | accessdate = 2009-10-07}}</ref>

==Terminology ==
{{See|Section Thirty-five of the Constitution Act, 1982}}

The terms First Peoples and First Nations are interchangeable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aidp.bc.ca/terminology_of_native_aboriginal_metis.pdf|title=Terminology of First Nations, Native, Aboriginal and Metis (NAHO)|work=aidp.bc.ca/| accessdate =2009-10-05}}</ref>  The terms First Peoples or Aboriginals in Canada are normally broader terms than First Nations, as they include Inuit, M<U+00E9>tis and First Nations. First Nations (most often used in the plural) has come into general use for the [[Indigenous peoples of North America]] located in [[History of Canada|Canada]], and their descendants, who are neither Inuit nor M<U+00E9>tis.  First Nations person is used on [[List of Indian reserves in Canada|reserves]] is being supplanted by members of various nations referring to themselves by their group or national identity.  In conversation this would be as "I am Haida," or "we are Kwantlens," in recognition of their First Nations ethnicities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Language and Identity |url=http://books.google.ca/books?hl=en&lr=&id=wwvOjiqyU-EC&oi=fnd&pg=PA1&ots=OK_P0NFcal&sig=uDCDiaXehYXADZaVw58-NFW4YW0#v=onepage&q=&f=false|format=Digitised online by Google books|first= John |last=Edwards |publisher= Cambridge University Press| accessdate =2009-10-05 }}</ref>  In this [[Section Thirty-five of the Constitution Act, 1982|Act]], "Aboriginal peoples of Canada" includes the Indian, Inuit and M<U+00E9>tis peoples of Canada.<ref name="defe">{{cite web
  | title =  Constitution Act, 1982 Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms 
  | work = Department of Justice
  | publisher = Government of Canada
  | date = 1982
  | url = http://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&source=web&ct=res&cd=1&url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.solon.org%2FConstitutions%2FCanada%2FEnglish%2Fca_1982.html&ei=nWDLSvCiO4u8MJ_LzMwD&usg=AFQjCNEkOhvaVRMaH-74hX6cGqr0qpSX_Q
  | accessdate =2009-10-05 }}
</ref>

Indian remains in place as the legal term used in the [[Constitution of Canada|Canadian Constitution]], its usage outside such situations can be considered offensive.  Aboriginals is more commonly used to describe all Indigenous peoples of Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ainc-inac.gc.ca/ap/tln-eng.asp|title=Terminology|work=Indian and Northern Affairs Canada| accessdate =2009-10-05 }}</ref>  It also refers to self-identification of Aboriginal people who live within Canada claiming rights of Sovereignty or Aboriginal title to lands.

The term Eskimo has [[pejorative]] connotations and in Canada and Greenland. Indigenous peoples have replaced the term Eskimo with Inuit.<ref name=eski>{{cite web|url=http://www.expansionistparty.org/Eskimo.html|title="Eskimo" vs. "Inuit"|work=Expansionist Party of the United States  | accessdate =2009-10-05 }}</ref>  The Yupik of Alaska and Siberia do not consider themselves Inuit, and ethnographers agree they are a distinct people.<ref name="kaplan">{{cite web
  | last = Kaplam
  | first = Lawrence
  | title = Inuit or Eskimo: Which names to use?
  | publisher = [[Alaska Native Language Center]], [[University of Alaska Fairbanks]]
  | date = 2002
  | url = http://www.uaf.edu/anlc/inuitoreskimo.html
  | accessdate =2007-04-06 }}
</ref><ref name=eski/> They prefer the terminology Yupik, Yupiit, or Eskimo.  The [[Yupik languages]] are linguistically distinct from the [[Inuit languages]].<ref name="kaplan"/> Linguistic groups of Arctic people have no universal replacement term for Eskimo, inclusive of all Inuit and Yupik people across the geographical area inhabited by the Inuit and Yupik peoples.<ref name="kaplan"/>

== History ==
===Lithic period ===
{{See also|Models of migration to the New World|Paleo-Indian|Clovis culture}} 
[[File:Journal.pone.0001596.g004.png|thumb|left|200px|alt="Three maps of prehistoric America. (A) Divergence, then gradual population expansion of the Amerind ancestors from their East Central Asian gene pool (blue arrow). (B) Proto-Amerind occupation of Beringia with little to no population growth for <U+2248>20,000 years. (C) Rapid colonization of the New World by a founder group migrating southward through the ice free, inland corridor between the eastern Laurentide and western Cordilleran Ice Sheets (green arrow) and/or along the Pacific coast (red arrow). In (B), the exposed seafloor is shown at its greatest extent during the last glacial maximum at <U+2248>20<U+2013>18 kya [25]. In (A) and (C), the exposed seafloor is depicted at <U+2248>40 kya and <U+2248>16 kya, when prehistoric sea levels were comparable.  A scaled-down version of Beringia today (60% reduction of A<U+2013>C) is presented in the lower left corner. This smaller map highlights the Bering Strait that has geographically separated the New World from Asia since <U+2248>11<U+2013>10 kya."|Maps depicting each phase of a  three-step colonisation model for the peopling of the Americas.]]
According to [[archeological]] and [[Genetics|genetic]] evidence, North and South America were the last continents in the world with [[early human migrations|human habitation]].<ref name="national"/> During the ([[Wisconsin glaciation]]), 50,000{{emdash}}17,000 years ago, falling [[sea level]]s allowed people to move across the [[Bering land bridge]] that joined [[Siberia]] to north west North America (Alaska).<ref name="national">{{cite web
  | title = Atlas of the Human Journey-The Genographic Project
  | publisher = National Geographic Society.
  | date = 1996-2008 
  | url = https://genographic.nationalgeographic.com/genographic/atlas.html?era=e003
  | accessdate =  2009-10-06}}
</ref> Alaska was [[glacial refugia|ice-free]] due to [[precipitation shadow|low snowfall]], allowing a [[small population size|small population]] to exist. The [[Laurentide ice sheet]] covered the majority of Canada blocking [[nomadic]] inhabitants and confining them to Alaska (East [[Beringia]]) for thousands of years.<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Pielou
  | first = E.C.
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = After the Ice Age : The Return of Life to Glaciated North America
  | publisher =  [[University of Chicago Press|University Of Chicago Press]]
  | date = 1991
  | isbn =0-226-66812-6 }}
</ref>  

[[Mitochondrial]] [[DNA]] indicates that the first inhabitants of the Americas share a single ancestral population, one that developed in isolation, conjectured to be Beringia.<ref name="aaa"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.physorg.com/news169474130.html |title=The peopling of the Americas: Genetic ancestry influences health|work=Scientific American| accessdate =2009-10-06}}</ref> The isolation of these peoples in Beringia might have lasted 5,000{{emdash}}15,000 years.<ref name="nda">{{cite book
  | last = Sigur<U+011F>ard<U+00F3>ttir
  | first = S
  | coauthors = Guicher JR, Stefansson K, Donnelly P
  | title =  The mutation rate in the human [[Mitochondrial DNA|mtDNA]] control region.
  | publisher = PubMed Central
|journal=Am J Hum Genet
|volume=66:1599<U+2013>1609
  | date = 2000
|format=published online April 7, 2000
  | url = http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1378010/
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|format=pdf
}}
</ref> Around 16,500 years ago, the [[Last Glacial Maximum|glaciers began melting]], allowing people to move south and east into Canada and beyond.<ref name="aaa">{{cite journal
  | last = Tamm
  | first = Erika 
  | coauthors = et al
  | title = Beringian Standstill and Spread of Native American Founders
  | journal = [[PLoS ONE]]
  | volume = 2(9): e829. 
  | publisher = Public Library of Science
  | location = 
  | date =  2007 September 5
  | url = http://www.pubmedcentral.nih.gov/articlerender.fcgi?artid=1952074
  | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0000829
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}
</ref> 

The first inhabitants entered the Americas pursuing [[Pleistocene]] mammals such as the [[Giant Beaver|giant beaver]], [[steppe wisent]], [[musk ox]], [[mastodons]], [[Woolly mammoth|woolly mammoths]] and  ancient reindeer (early caribou).<ref name="Gibbard">{{cite web
  | last = Gibbard
  | first = P
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = van Kolfschoten, T. 
  | title = A Geologic Time Scale 
|chapter=The Pleistocene and Holocene Epochs
  | work = Gowin Institute for Quaternary Research
  | publisher = Quaternary Palaeoenvironments Group, Department of Geography, University of Cambridge
|Location=[[Cambridge University Press]], UK
  | date = 2004
|chapter 22
|isbn=0521781426
  | url = http://www-qpg.geog.cam.ac.uk/people/gibbard/GTS2004Quat.pdf 
  | format = pdf
  | accessdate =2009-10-18 }}</ref>  One route hypothesized is that people walked south via an ice-free corridor on the east side of the [[Rocky Mountains]], and then fanned out across North America before continuing on to South America.<ref name="albert">{{cite web |url=http://albertajasper.com/Alberta-History-pre-1800.html |title=Alberta History pre 1800{{emdash}}Jasper Alberta |work=AlbertaJasper.com | accessdate = 2009-10-06}}</ref>  The other conjectured route is that they migrated, either on foot or using [[boat#history|primitive boats]], down the [[Pacific Coast]] to the tip of South America, and then crossed the Rockies and [[Andes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archaeology.about.com/gi/o.htm?zi=1/XJ&zTi=1&sdn=archaeology&cdn=education&tm=25&f=00&tt=13&bt=1&bts=1&zu=http%3A//www.jstor.org/stable/279189|title=Alternate Migration Corridors for Early Man in North America|work=American Antiquity, Vol. 44, No. 1 (Jan., 1979), p2 | accessdate = 2009-10-06}}</ref> Evidence of the latter has been covered by a [[sea level rise]] of hundreds of metres following the last ice age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realclimate.org/index.php/archives/2009/01/sea-will-rise-to-levels-of-last-ice-age/|title=68 Responses to Sea will rise <U+2018>to levels of last Ice Age|work=Center for Climate Systems Research, Columbia University | accessdate = 2009-10-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last = Harris
  | first = A.G.
  | coauthors = E. Tuttle, S.D. Tuttle,
  | title = Geology of National Parks
|edition=5
  | publisher =  Kendall/Hunt Publishing
|isbn=0-7872-5353-7
|location=Iowa
  | date = 1997
  | url = http://books.google.ca/books?id=Xr7v7GNmHs0C&dq=Geology+of+National+Parks&printsec=frontcover&source=bl&ots=Vau55QJTJO&sig=0EVX3H9AX6mgjXzp41F0JOzbLbM&hl=en&ei=n4TbSqn0MJLWNsSn2eYH&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CBEQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=&f=false
  | format = 6th edition is online by Google Books
  | accessdate = 2009-10-18}}</ref> 

The Old Crow Flats and basin was one of the areas in Canada untouched by glaciations during the [[Quaternary glaciation|Pleistocene Ice ages]], thus it served as a pathway and refuge for ice age plants and animals.<ref name="mountain">{{cite web
  | title = Life in Crow Flats-Part 1
  | work = Old Crow's official Website
  | publisher = Vuntut Gwitchin First Nation 
  | date = 1998-2009 
  | url = http://www.oldcrow.ca/cf1.htm
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}</ref> The area holds evidence of early human habitation in North America dating from  about 30,000 years ago and ending about [[9th millennium BC|11,000 years ago]].<ref name="olcrow">{{Cite web|url=http://www.taiga.net/wetlands/oldcrow/oc_gen.html|title=Old Crow Flats|work=TAIGN co-operative environmental and community web network dedicated to Northern Canada & Alaska|accessdate=2009-10-05}}</ref> Fossils from the area include some never accounted for in North America like [[hyena]]s and large [[camel]]s.<ref name="taiga.net">{{Cite web|url=http://www.taiga.net/wetlands/oldcrow/oc_gen.html|title=Old Crow Flats|publisher=taiga.net|accessdate=2007-08-05}}</ref> Bluefish Caves is an archaeological site in the [[Yukon|Yukon Territory]] of Canada from which a specimen of apparently human-worked mammoth bone has been radiocarbon dated to 18,000 years ago.<ref name=Griebel>{{cite web
  | last = Griebel
  | first = Ron 
  | title = The Bluefish Caves
  | publisher = Minnesota State University 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.mnsu.edu/emuseum/archaeology/sites/northamerica/bluefishcaves.html
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}
</ref> Another team has discovered characteristics of human-worked mammoth bone flakes in the Bluefish Caves area, radiocarbon dated to an even earlier period of 24,000 years ago.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Beringia: humans were here
  | work = Gazette (Montreal) 
  | publisher = CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc.
  | date = May 17, 2008
  | url = http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/saturdayextra/story.html?id=2a31375e-e834-407d-b8db-2a0010ad4acf&p=2
  | format = re-published online by Canada.com
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}
</ref> 
[[Image:Clovis Point.jpg<U+200E>|thumb|right|upright|alt="Clovis fluted blade 11,000 years old"|Example of a Clovis fluted blade that is 11,000 years old</br><small>Image courtesy of the Virginia Dept. of Historic Resources.</small>]]
During the 1950s, geologists first conjectured that an ice-free corridor ran north and south through Alberta during the [[Last glacial period|Late Wisconsin period]].<ref>{{cite book
|last=Wilson
|first=M. C.
|coauthors=J. A. Burns 
|editor=R. Bonnichsen and K. L. Turnmire
|title=Ice Age People of North America: Environments, Origins and Adaptations
|date=1999
|publisher=Oregon State University Press and Center for the Study of the First Americans
|location=Corvallis, Oregon
|pages=213
|chapter=Searching for the earliest Canadians: wide corridors, narrow doorways, small windows
|isbn=9780870714580 
}}
</ref><ref name="albert"/> Stone scrapers and choppers were preserved from archaeological sites in [[Bow River|Grimshaw, Bow River]], and [[Lethbridge]].<ref name="albert">{{cite book
|last=Dickason
|first=Olive
|title=Canada's First Nations: A History of the Founding Peoples from the Earliest Times
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|publisher= [[Oxford University Press]]
|location=Toronto
|language=
|isbn=0-19-541358-X
}}
</ref> These stone tools discovered under glacial sand and gravel are classified as pre-glacial and indicate nomadic humans occupied the area as early as 25,000 years ago.<ref name="albert"/> Archaeologists are still finalising the dates recorded for the Alberta and the Old Crow flats sites.<ref>{{cite book
  | last =  Gibbon 
  | first = Guy E.
  | coauthors = Kenneth M. Ames
  | title = Archaeology of prehistoric native America: an encyclopedia
|date=1998
  | publisher = Taylor & Francis.
|format=Re-published online by Google books
  | pages = 682
  | url = http://books.google.ca/books?id=_0u2y_SVnmoC&pg=RA1-PA682&lpg=RA1-PA682&dq=old+crow+caves+debate&source=bl&ots=OQs3QyVT5I&sig=4mAK2XU-uUV6dpJCa7I6hEwtQlQ&hl=en&ei=ul2gSqjjGqif8QaHo6zpDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4#v=onepage&q=old%20crow%20caves%20debate&f=false
| accessdate = 2009-10-06}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last = Chlachula and
  | first = Jiri 
  | coauthors =  Louise Leslie
  | title = Preglacial archaeological evidence at Grimshaw, the Peace River area, Alberta: Reply1
  | work = NRC Canada
  | publisher = Government of Canada
  | date = 2001
  | url = http://pubs.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/rp/rppdf/e01-030.pdf
  | format = pdf
  | accessdate = 2009-10-06}}
</ref>

Clovis sites dated at 13,500 years ago were discovered in western North America during the 1930s. [[Clovis people]] were regarded as the first wide spread human inhabitants of the [[New World]] and ancestors of indigenous peoples in North and South America.<ref name="cloves">{{cite book |title=Ice Age People of North America |last=Lepper |first=Bradley T. |authorlink= |editor=Bonnichsen, Robson; Turnmire, Karen |year=1999 |publisher=Oregon State University Press |location=Corvallis |isbn=9780870714 |pages=362-394 |chapter=Pleistocene Peoples of Midcontinental North America | accessdate = 2009-10-06}}</ref>Archaeological discoveries in the past thirty years have brought forward other distinctive Paleo-Indian cultures who occupied North America from the lower [[Great Plains]] to the shores of [[Chile]].<ref name="Firestone2007">{{ cite journal | last = Firestone | first = R. B. | authorlink = | coauthors = et al. | year = 2007 | month = | title = Evidence for an extraterrestrial impact 12,900 years ago that contributed to the megafaunal extinctions and the Younger Dryas cooling | journal = [[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|PNAS]] | volume = 104 | issue = 41 | pages = 16016-16021 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0706977104 | url = | accessdate =2009-09-18 | quote =| pmid = 17901202 |isbn=0870714589 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.friendsofthewildwest.com/archaeology.html|title=History of Alberta-The Ancient Past|work=Friends of the Wild West Agriculture & Music Society| accessdate = 2009-10-05}}</ref> 

Localised regional cultures developed from the time of the [[Younger Dryas]] cold climate period which dated 12,900 <U+2013> 11,500 years ago.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Kennett DJ, Kennett JP, West A, et al. |title=Nanodiamonds in the younger dryas boundary sediment layer |journal=Science (journal) |volume=323 |issue=5910 |pages=94 |year=2009 |month=January |pmid=19119227 |doi=10.1126/science.1162819 |url=|accessdate=2009-10-06 |quote= }}</ref> The [[Folsom tradition]]  are characterised by their use of [[Folsom point]]s as projectile tips at archaelogical sites.  These tools assisted activities at kill sites which marked the slaughter and butchering of bison.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Hillerman
|first= Anthony G.
|title=The Great Taos Bank Robbery and Other Indian Country Affairs.  
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|date=1978
|publisher=[[University of New Mexico]] press
|isbn=0-8263-0306-4
|chapter=The Hunt for the Lost American}}
</ref>
[[File:Beringia land bridge-noaagov.gif|thumb|left|300px|alt=Animation of the Beringia Land Bridge located between north east Eurasia and north west Americas and its evolution between 21,000 BC to modern times.|Shrinking of the Bering land bridge 21,000 BC to present]]
The land bridge existed until 13,000{{emdash}}11,000 years ago, long after the oldest proven human settlements in the New World began.<ref name=mapSurvey>{{cite web |url=http://www.erudit.org/revue/GPQ/1988/v42/n1/032714ar.pdf |format=pdf |work=Dyke A.S. & Prest V.K |title=Late Wisconsinian and Holocene retreat of the Larentide ice sheet. vol. 42, n<U+00B0> 1, 1988, p. 101-102 |publisher= [[Geological Survey of Canada]] | accessdate =2009-10-17}} </ref> Lower sea levels in the [[Queen Charlotte Sound (Canada)|Queen Charlotte sound]] and [[Hecate Strait]] produced great grass lands called ''archipelago of Haida Gwaii''.<ref name="hadi">{{cite web
  | title =  Prehistory of Haida Gwaii
  | work = Civilization.ca-Haida-The people and the land-Prehistory
|Publisher=Canadian Museum of Civilization Corporation
  | date = June 8, 2001
  | url = http://www.civilization.ca/cmc/exhibitions/aborig/haida/happr01e.shtml
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}</ref>
[[Hunter-gatherer]]s left [[Clovis point|Clovis fluted stone tools]] and the remains of large butchered mammals, occupying the area from 13,000{{emdash}}[[7th millennium BC|9,000 years ago]].<ref name="hadi"/> In July of 1992, the Federal Government officially designated [[X<U+0332><U+00E1>:ytem]] as a National Historic Site, one of the first Indigenous spiritual sites in Canada to be formally recognised in this manner.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = X<U+0332><U+00E1>:ytem: A cultural, historic and spiritual First Nations site--X<U+0332><U+00E1>:ytem Longhouse Interpretive Centre, Mission, BC, Canada
  | publisher = X<U+0332><U+00E1>:ytem Longhouse Interpretive Centre,
  | date = 2003-2009 
  | url = http://www.xaytem.ca/archives.php 
  | accessdate = 2009-09-18}}
</ref>

The Plano culture was a group of hunter-gatherer communities that occupied the Great Plains area of North America between 12,000{{mdash}}10,000 years ago.<ref name="palo">{{cite web
  | last =  Reynolds
  | first = Graham
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = Richard MacKinnon, Ken MacDonald and Folkus Atlantic Productions
  | title = Period 1 (10,000{{emdash}}8,000 years ago) Palaeo-Indian culture
  | work =  Learners Portal
  | url = http://www.learnersportal.com/CanadaFP/Ancient/per1.html
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}
</ref> The Paleo-Indians moved into new territory as it emerged from under the glaciers.  Big game flourished in this new environment.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Early North American Cultures
  | work = MSU EMuseum 
  | publisher = Minnesota State University
  | date = 2007
  | url = http://www.mnsu.edu/emuseum/prehistory/northamerica/culture/index.html
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}
</ref> The Plano culture are characterised by a range of projectile point tools collectively called [[Plano point]]s which were used to hunt [[bison]].  Their diets also included [[pronghorn antelope]], [[elk]], [[deer]], [[raccoon]] and [[coyote]].<ref name="palo"/> At the beginning of the [[Archaic period in the Americas|Archaic Era]] they began to adopt a sedentary approach to subsistence.<ref name="palo"/> Sites in and around [[Belmont, Nova Scotia]] have evidence of Plano-Indians, indicating small seasonal hunting camps, perhaps re-visited over generations from around 11,000{{emdash}}10,000 years ago.<ref name="palo"/> Seasonal large and smaller game fish and fowl were food and raw material sources. Adaptation to the harsh environment included tailored clothing and skin-covered tents on wooden frames.<ref name="palo"/>
{{clear}}

===Archaic period===
{{See also|List of pre-Columbian cultures |Category:Archaeological cultures of North America}}
The North American climate finally stabilised by 8000&nbsp; [[Common Era|before the Common Era ]] BCE 
(10,000 years ago), climatic conditions were very  similar to today's.<ref name="icaage">{{cite book
|last=Imbrie
|first=J
|coauthors= K.P.Imbrie
|title=Ice Ages: Solving the Mystery 
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|date=1979
|publisher=Enslow Publishers
|location=Short Hills NJ
|isbn=0226668118
}}
</ref>  This led to wide spread migration, [[cultivation]] and subsequently a  dramatic rise in population all over the  Americas.<ref name="icaage"/>  Over the course of thousands of years, American indigenous peoples domesticated, bred and cultivated a large array of plant species.  These species now constitute 50<U+2013>60% of all crops in cultivation worldwide.<ref>{{cite book
|last=United States. Foreign Agricultural Service
|title=Foreign agriculture
|trans_title=
|volume=24
|date=1962
|publisher= Bureau of Agricultural Economics
|location=United States
|pages=167
}}
</ref>  
[[File:Na-Dene langs.png|thumb|right|alt="Map of North America showing in red the pre-contact distribution of Na-Dene languages"|Distribution of Na-Dene languages shown in red]]
The vastness and variety of Canada's climates, [[ecology]], [[vegetation]], [[fauna]], and landform separations have defined ancient peoples implicitly into cultural or [[Linguistics|linguistic]] divisions. Canada is surrounded north, east, and west with coastline and since the last ice age Canada has consisted of distinct forest regions.  Language contributes to the identity of a people by influenceing social life ways and spiritual practices.<ref name="prepre"/>  Aboriginal religions developed from [[anthropomorphism]] and [[animism]] philosophies.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Friesen
|first=John
|title=Rediscovering the [[List of First Nations peoples|First Nations of Canada]]. 
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|date=1997
|publisher=Detselig Enterprises Ltd
|location=Calgary, AB
|isbn=1550591436
}}
</ref> 

The placement of artifacts and materials within an Archaic burial site indicated social differentiation based upon status.<ref name="icaage"/> There is a continuous record of occupation of [[St<U+00F3>:l<U+014D>|S'<U+00F3>lh T<U+00E9>m<U+00E9>xw]] by Aboriginal people dating from the early [[Holocene]] period, 10,000{{emdash}}9,000 years ago.<ref name="thor">{{cite book
|editorn=Carlson, Keith Thor
|title=You Are Asked to Witness: The St<U+00F3>:l<U+014D> in Canada's Pacific Coast History
|year=1997
|publisher= St<U+00F3>:l<U+014D> Heritage Trust
|location=Chilliwack, BC
|isbn= 0-9681577-0-X
}}
</ref> Archaeological sites at [[Stave Lake]], [[Coquitlam Lake]], [[Fort Langley, British Columbia|Fort Langley]] and region uncovered early period artifacts. These early inhabitants were highly mobile hunter-gatherers, consisting of approximately 20 to 50 members of an extended family.<ref>{{cite web |author=Jacobs, James Q. |year=2002 |title=Paleoamerican Origins by James Q. Jacobs |work=Paleoamerican Origins: A Review of Hypotheses and Evidence Relating to the Origins of the First Americans |url=http://www.jqjacobs.net/anthro/paleoamerican_origins.html |work=Anthropology and Archaeology Pages |publisher=jqjacobs.net|accessdate=2009-10-02}}</ref><ref name="thor"/> The [[Na-Dene languages|Na-Dene]] people occupied much of the land area of northwest and central North America starting around 8,000&nbsp;BCE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyandtheheadlines.abc-clio.com/ContentPages/ContentPage.aspx?entryId=1171754&currentSection=1161468&productid=5|title=American Indian Heritage Month: Commemoration vs. Exploitation|work=ABC-CLIO|accessdate=2009-10-02}}</ref> They were the earliest ancestors of the [[Athabascan]]-speaking peoples, including the [[Navajo people|Navajo]] and [[Apache]]. They had villages with large multi-family dwellings, used seasonally during the summer from which they hunted, fished and gathered food supplies for the winter.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Leer
|first=Jeff
|coauthors= Doug Hitch, & John Ritter
|title=Interior [[Tlingit noun]] dictionary: The dialects spoken by Tlingit elders of Carcross and [[Teslin, Yukon]], and [[Atlin, British Columbia]]
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|date=2001
|publisher=Yukon Native Language Centre
|location=[[Whitehorse, Yukon]] Territory
|isbn=1-55242-227-5
}}
</ref> The [[Wendat]] peoples settled into [[Southern Ontario]] along the [[Eramosa River]] around 8,000{{emdash}}7,000&nbsp;BCE (10,000{{emdash}}9,000&nbsp;years ago).<ref name="ray"/> They were concentrated between [[Lake Simcoe]] and [[Georgian Bay]]. Wendat hunted caribou to survive on the glacier covered land.<ref name="ray">{{cite book
|last=Ray
|first= Arthur J.
|title=I Have Lived Here Since The World Began: An Illustrated [[History of Canada]]'s Native People
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|date=1996
|publisher= Lester Publishing
|location=Toronto, ON
|isbn=155263633X
}}</ref>  Many different First Nations cultures relied upon the buffalo starting by 6,000{{emdash}}5,000&nbsp;BCE (8,000{{emdash}}7,000&nbsp;years ago).<ref name="ray"/> They hunted buffalo by herding migrating buffalo off cliffs. [[Head-Smashed-In Buffalo Jump]], near [[Lethbridge, Alberta]], is a hunting grounds which was in use for about 5,000 years.<ref name="ray"/> 

The west coast of Canada by 7,000{{emdash}}5000&nbsp;BCE (9,000{{emdash}}7,000&nbsp;years ago) saw various cultures who organised themselves around the salmon fishing.<ref name="ray"/> The [[Nuu-chah-nulth]] of [[Vancouver Island]] began whaling with advanced long spears at about this time.<ref name="ray"/> The [[Maritime Archaic]] is one group of North American [[Archaic stage|Archaic]] culture of sea-mammal hunters in the [[subarctic]]. They prospered from approximately 7,000&nbsp;BCE{{emdash}}1,500&nbsp;BCE (9,000{{emdash}}3,500 years ago) along the [[Atlantic Coast]] of North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.therooms.ca/museum/mnotes12.asp|title=
Museum Notes-The Maritime Archaic Tradition|work=By James A. Tuck-The Rooms Provincial Art Gallery|accessdate=2009-10-05}}</ref>  Their settlements included [[long house|longhouses]], and boat topped temporary or seasonal houses. They engaged in long-distance trade, with white [[chert]], a rock quarried from northern Labrador to Maine.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Tuck
|first=J. A.
|title=The excavation of an Archaic Indian Cemetery in Newfoundland. Newfoundland Social and Economic Studies 17
|date=1976
|publisher=Institute of Social and Economic Research
|location=St. John's
|chapter=Ancient peoples of Port au Choix
|isbn=0919666124
}}
</ref> The [[Pre-Columbian]] culture called [[Red Paint People]] are indigenous to the [[New England]] and [[Atlantic Canada]] regions of North America.  They flourished between 3,000&nbsp;BCE{{emdash}}1,000&nbsp;BCE (5,000{{emdash}}3,000&nbsp;years ago) and were named after their burials, which used large quantities of [[ochre]], normally red, to cover both bodies and grave goods.<ref>{{cite web
|title=The so-called "Red Paint People
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|date=1997
|publisher=University of Maine
|work=Brian Robinson 
|url=http://www.seacoastnh.com/history/prehistoric/redpaint.html
}}</ref>[[Image:Cambridge Bay Thule Site 1998-06-28.jpg|thumb|left|alt="Photograph of rocks depicting an archaeological Thule Site (Copper Inuit) near the waters of Cambridge Bay (Victoria Island)"|[[Thule people|Thule]] site (Victoria Island)]]

The [[Arctic small tool tradition]] is a broad cultural entity that developed along the [[Alaska Peninsula]], around [[Bristol Bay]], and on the eastern shores of the Bering Strait around [[25th century BC|2,500&nbsp;BCE]] (4,500&nbsp;years ago).<ref name="Fagan">{{cite book
|last=Fagan
|first=Brian M.
|title=Ancient North America: The Archaeology of a Continent.
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|edition=4
|date=2005
|publisher=Thames & Hudson Inc.
|location=New York
|pages=390, p396
|isbn=0500281483
}}
</ref>  These peoples had a highly distinctive toolkit of small blades (microblades) that were pointed at both ends and used as side or end barbs on [[arrows]] or spears made of other materials, such as [[bone]] or [[antler]].  [[Scraper (archaeology)|Scraper]]s, engraving tools and [[adze]] blades were also included in their toolkits.<ref name="Fagan"/> The Arctic Small Tool tradition branches off into two cultural variants, including the Pre-Dorset, and Independence traditions. These two groups, ancestors of Thule people, were displaced by the Inuit by 1000&nbsp;[[Common Era|Common Era]] (CE).<ref name="Fagan"/>{{rp|179-81}}
{{clear}}

===Post-Archaic period===
{{Annotated image | float=right 
| image=Hopewellsphere2 map HRoe 2008.jpg
| width=200
| imageleft=-150
|height=100
| caption=Great Lakes area of the [[Hopewell tradition|Hopewell Interaction Area]] <br />PP{{=}}[[Point Peninsula Complex]]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;S=[[Saugeen Complex]]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;L=[[Laurel Complex]]
|image-width=200
| alt=A northerly section focusing on the Saugeen, Laurel and Point Peninsula complexes of the map showing south eastern United States and the Great Lakes area of Canada showing the Hopewell Interaction Sphere and in different colours the various local expressions of the Hopewell cultures, including the Laurel Complex, Saugeen Complex, Point Peninsula Complex, Marksville culture, Copena culture, Kansas City Hopewell, Swift Creek Culture, Goodall Focus, Crab Orchard culture and Havana Hopewell culture.
|float = right
|annotations=
{{Annotation|148|28|'''PP'''}}
{{Annotation|130|45|'''S'''}}
{{Annotation|115|10|'''L'''}}
}}
The [[Old Copper Complex]] societies date from 3,000&nbsp;BCE{{mdash}}500&nbsp;BCE (5,000{{emdash}}2,500&nbsp;years ago) are a manifestation of the [[Woodland period|Woodland Culture]], and are pre-pottery in nature.<ref  name="Winchell">{{cite book
|last=Winchell
|first=N.H.
|title=Ancient Copper Mines of Isle Royale,
|volume=19
|date=1881
|publisher=[[Popular Science]] Monthly
|location=New York
|pages=601-2
}}
</ref> Evidence is found in the northern [[Great Lakes]] regions.  They  extracted [[copper]] from local glacial deposits and utilised it in its natural form to manufacture tools and implements.<ref  name="Winchell"/> 

The Woodland cultural period dates from about 2,000&nbsp;BCE{{mdash}}1,000&nbsp;CE and locates in Ontario, Quebec, and Maritime regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/history/seac/woodland.htm|title=The Woodland Period ca. 2000&nbsp;BC-AD 1000|work=The Southeast Archeological Center (SEAC) | accessdate = 2009-10-05}}</ref> The introduction of pottery distinguishes the Woodland culture from the earlier Archaic stage inhabitants. [[Laurentides|Laurentian]] people of southern Ontario manufactured the oldest pottery excavated in Canada.<ref name="prepre"/> They created pointed-bottom beakers decorated by a cord marking technique that involved impressing tooth implements into wet clay. Woodland technology included items such as beaver incisor knives, bangles, and chisels.  The population practicing sedentary agricultural life ways continued to increase on a diet of squash, corn, and bean crops.<ref name="prepre">{{cite book
|last=Fagan
|first=Brian M
|others=University of California
|title=People of the Earth: An Introduction to World Prehistory
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|date=1992
|publisher=[[HarperCollins|Harper Collins]]
|isbn=032101457X
}}
</ref> 

The Hopewell tradition is an Aboriginal culture that flourished along American rivers from 300&nbsp;BCE{{mdash}}500&nbsp;CE. At its greatest extent, the [[Hopewell Exchange System]] networked [[culture]]s and societies with the peoples on the Canadian shores of [[Lake Ontario]]. Canadian expression of the Hopewellian peoples encompass the [[Point Peninsula Complex|Point Peninsula]], [[Saugeen Complex|Saugeen]], and [[Laurel Complex|Laurel complexes]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = A History of the Native People of Canada 
  | work = Dr. James V. Wright
  | publisher = [[Canadian Museum of Civilization]]
  | date = 2009
  | url = http://www.civilization.ca/cmc/exhibitions/archeo/hnpc/npvol25e.shtml
  | accessdate = 2009-10-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Ohio Historical Society |url =http://www.ohiohistorycentral.org/entry.php?rec=1283 | title = Hopewell Culture-Ohio History Central-A product of the Ohio Historical Society|publisher=Hopewell-Ohio History Central|date=2009|accessdate=2009-09-18}}</ref><ref name="Price">{{cite book | author= Douglas T. Price, and Gary M. Feinman | year= 2008 | title= Images of the Past, 5th edition | pages= 274<U+2013>277 | location= New York | publisher=McGraw-Hill | isbn= 978-0 07-3405209 |accessdate=2009-09-18}}</ref>  

====First Nations ====
{{Main|First Nations}}
[[File:Chief George and daughter.jpg|thumb|left|alt="Black an white photograph of Skwxwu7mesh Chief George from the village of Senakw with his daughter in traditional regalia."|Chief George from the village of Senakw with his daughter in traditional regalia, c.1906]]
First Nations peoples had settled and established trade routes across what is now Canada by 500&nbsp;BCE{{mdash}}1,000&nbsp;CE. Communities developed each with their own culture, customs, and character.<ref name="Joe">{{cite book
|last=Joe
|first=Rita
|coauthors=Lesley Choyce
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|title=The Native Canadian Anthology
|date= 2005
|publisher=Nimbus Publishing (CN)
|isbn= 1-895900-04-2
}}
</ref>  In the northwest were the [[Athapaskan]], [[Slavey]], [[Dogrib]], [[Tutchone]], and  [[Tlingit]].  Along the Pacific coast were the [[Haida]], [[Salish]], [[Kwakiutl]], [[Nuu-chah-nulth|Nootka]], [[Nisga'a]], [[Senakw]] and [[Gitxsan]]. In the plains were the [[Blackfoot]], [[Blood]], [[Sarcee]] and [[Blackfoot|Peigan]]. In the northern woodlands were the [[Cree]] and [[Chipewyan]]. Around the Great Lakes were the [[Anishinaabe]], [[Algonquin]], [[M<U+00ED>kmaq]], [[Iroquois]] and [[Huron]]. Along the Atlantic coast were the [[Beothuk]], [[Maliseet]], [[Innu]], [[Abenaki]] and [[Micmac]]. 

Many Canadian Aboriginal [[civilization|civilisation]]s established characteristics and hallmarks which included permanent or urban settlements, [[agriculture]], civic and monumental architecture, and [[complex society|complex societal hierarchies]].<ref name="Complex ">{{Citation
  | author = [[Peter Turchin]], [[Leonid Grinin]], [[Andrey Korotayev]], and Victor C. de Munck.Turchin  
  | title = History and mathematics: Historical Dynamics and Development of Complex Societies
|format=URSS.ru-Books on Science-On-line Bookstore. 
  | url = http://edurss.ru/cgi-bin/db.pl?lang=en&blang=en&page=Book&id=53185
|editor= Moscow: KomKniga/[[Editorial URSS|URSS]], 2006. |isbn=5484010020 |accessdate=2009-10-18
}}</ref> These civilisations had evolved and changed by the time of the first permanent European arrivals (c. late 15th<U+2013>early [[16th century|16th centuries]]), and have been brought forward through archaeological investigations.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Willey
|first=Gordon R
|authorlink=
|coauthors=Philip Phillips 
|firstn= |lastn=
|title=Method and Theory in American Archaeology
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|date=1957
|publisher= University of Chicago Press
|isbn=978-0-226-89888-9
|pages=1(introduction) 
}}
 </ref> 

There are indications of contact made before [[Christopher Columbus]] between the first peoples and those from other continents.  Aboriginal people in Canada interacted with Europeans as far back as [[1000 AD]], but prolonged contact came after Europeans established permanent settlements in the 17th and 18th centuries.<ref name="Woodcock, part I">{{cite book
|author=[[George Woodcock]]
|title=A Social History of Canada
|accessdate=2009-10-06
|date=January 25, 1990
|publisher=Penguin Books Ltd 
|isbn=0140105360,978-0140105360
|chapter=Part 1
}}
</ref> In Columbus' time there was speculation that other Europeans had made the trip in ancient or contemporary times; [[Gonzalo Fern<U+00E1>ndez de Oviedo y Vald<U+00E9>s]] records in his ''General y natural historia de las Indias'' of 1526, which includes biographical information on Columbus.<ref name="Madrid">{{cite book
|last= de Amez<U+00FA>a
|first=Agust<U+00ED>n G.
|title=Introduction to the facsimile reprint of ''Libro de Claribalte''
|year=1956
|publisher=  [[Spanish Royal Academy]]Madrid
|location=Madrid
}}
</ref>  European written accounts generally recorded friendliness on the part of the First Nations, who profited in trade with Europeans.<ref name="Woodcock, part I"/>  Such trade generally strengthened the more organised political entities such as the [[Iroquois Confederation]].<ref>{{cite book
|author=[[Eric Wolf]]
|title=[[Europe and the People Without History]]
|accessdate=2009-10-06
|date=Dec 3, 1982
|publisher=University of California Press; 1 edition 
|isbn= 0520048989, 978-0520048980
|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/40564/Eric-Wolf-Europe-and-the-People-Without-History-introduction
|chapter=Chapter 6
}} URL gives introduction online </ref> Throughout the 16th century, European fleets made almost annual visits to the eastern shores of Canada to cultivate the fishing opportunities. A sideline industry emerged in the un-organised [[Fur trade|traffic of furs]] overseen by the [[Indian Department]].<ref>{{cite book |url=http://books.google.ca/books?id=oHlLvzRZ-1sC&pg=PA1&lpg=PA1&dq=fur+trade+and+the++Indian+Department&source=bl&ots=qzkRDrea54&sig=3aPGGpvSoCDz6M7b8mBCZU3vwio&hl=en&ei=mcbYSuDZKsjBlAfY0dihAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CA8Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=fur%20trade%20and%20the%20%20Indian%20Department&f=false |title=A Narrow Vision: Duncan Campbell Scott and the Administration of Indian |work=By E. Brian Titley|format=Re-published online by Google books |location=Vancouver |publisher=Univirsity Of British Columbia Press|date= 1992|isbn= 0774804203|accessdate=2009-10-15}}</ref>

Prominent First Nations people include Joe Capilano, who met with King of [[England]], [[Edward VII]], to speak of the need to settle [[land claims]] and [[Ovide Mercredi]], a leader at both the [[Meech Lake Accord]] constitutional reform discussions and [[Oka Crisis]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Ovide Mercredi installed as chancellor of Manitoba's newest university
  | publisher = CBC News
  | date = November 7, 2007
  | url = http://www.cbc.ca/canada/manitoba/story/2007/11/07/mercredi-chancellor.html
  | accessdate = 2009-10-03}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | title = The History of Metropolitan Vancouver's Hall of Fame Joe Capilano
  | url = http://www.vancouverhistory.ca/whoswho_C.htm
  | accessdate =2009-10-05 }}
</ref>

====Inuit====
{{Main|Inuit}}
The Inuit are the descendants of what [[Anthropology|anthropologist]]s call the Thule culture, who emerged from western Alaska around 1,000&nbsp;AD and spread eastwards across the [[Arctic]], displacing the [[Dorset culture]] (in [[Inuktitut]], the Tuniit). Inuit historically referred to the Tuniit as "giants", or "dwarfs", who were taller and stronger than the Inuit.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Rigby
  | first = Bruce
  | title = 101. Qaummaarviit Historic Park, Nunavut Handbook
  | url = http://www.nunavuthandbook.com/parks_pgs_297_331.pdf
  | format = pdf
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last = Wood
  | first = Shannon Raye
  | title = Tooth Wear and the Sexual Division of Labour in an Inuit Population
  | work = Department of Archaeology University of Saskatchewan
  | publisher = Simon Fraser University
  | date = April 1992
  | url = http://ir.lib.sfu.ca/bitstream/1892/5348/1/b14258730.pdf 
  | format =pdf
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref> Researchers hypothesize that the Dorset culture lacked dogs, larger weapons and other technologies used by the expanding Inuit society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historysociety.ca/content/en/pdfs/Jamieson2.pdf|title=The Dorsets: Depicting Culture Through Soapstone Carving|format=pdf  | accessdate =2009-10-05}}</ref> By 1,300, the Inuit had settled in west [[Greenland]], and finally moved into east Greenland over the following century. The Inuit had trade routes with more southern cultures. Boundary disputes were common and gave rise to aggressive actions.<ref name=warin>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritage.nf.ca/aboriginal/innu_culture.html|title=Innu Culture 3. Innu-Inuit 'Warfare'|work=1999, Adrian Tanner
Department of Anthropology-Memorial University of Newfoundland| accessdate =2009-10-05 }}</ref> 
[[File:Inuit hunter with harpoon.jpg|thumb|alt="black and white image of an Inuit hunter seated in a kayak holding a harpoon"|Inuk in a kayak, c. 1908-1914]]
[[War]]fare was common among Inuit groups with sufficient population density. Inuit, such as the [[Nunatamiut]] ([[Uummarmiut]]) who inhabited the [[Mackenzie River]] delta area, often engaged in common warfare.  The Central Arctic Inuit lacked the population density to engage in warfare. In the 13th century, the Thule culture began arriving in Greenland from what is now Canada. Norse accounts are scant. Norse-made items from Inuit campsites in Greenland were obtained by either trade or plunder.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heritage.nf.ca/aboriginal/inuit_history.html|title=Inuit Post-Contact History|work=Memorial University of Newfoundland and Labrador, Canada.| accessdate =2009-10-05 }}</ref> One account, [[:is:<U+00CD>var_B<U+00E1>r<U+00F0>arson|<U+00CD>var B<U+00E1>r<U+00F0>arson]], speaks of "small people" with whom the Norsemen fought.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Hans Christian Gull<U+00F8>v
|title=Gr<U+00F8>nlands Forhistorie
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|date=2005
|isbn=87-02-017245-5
|pages=17}}
</ref> [[14th century|14th-century]] accounts that a western settlement, one of the two Norse settlements, was taken over by the [[Skr<U+00E6>ling]].<ref>{{cite book
|last= Fitzhugh
|first=William W.
|editor=Fitzhugh, William W. and Elisabeth I. Ward, 
|title=Vikings: The [[Atlantic Ocean|North Atlantic]] Saga
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|year=2000
|publisher= [[Smithsonian Institution]]
|location=Washington, DC
|isbn= 15-60-98995-5
|pages=193-205
}}
</ref> 

After the disappearance of the Norse colonies in Greenland, the Inuit had no contact with Europeans for at least a century. By the mid 16th century, [[Basque people|Basque]] fishermen were already working the Labrador coast and had established whaling stations on land, such as been excavated at [[Red Bay, Newfoundland and Labrador|Red Bay]].<ref>{{cite book
  | last =McGhee 
  | first = Robert
  | title =  Northern Approaches. 
Before Columbus: Early European Visitors to the 
New World
  | publisher = The Beaver.Exploring Canada's History 
  | date =June/July 1992
|Volume=3
  | pages = 194
|isbn=12-18-094632-4
}}</ref>  The Inuit appear not to have interfered with their operations, but they raided the stations in winter for tools, and particularly worked iron, which they adapted to native needs.<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Kleivan
  | first = H
  | title = The Eskimos of Northeast Labrador
  | publisher = Norsk Polarinstitutt
Skrifter
  | date = 1966
|Volume = 139
|Page=9
|isbn=17-66-78922-6}}
</ref>

Notable among the Inuit are [[Abraham Ulrikab]] and family who became a [[zoo]] exhibit in [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]] and [[Tanya Tagaq Gillis]] who is a traditional [[Inuit throat singing|throat singer]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Minogue
  | first = Sarah
  | title = When Inuit become zoo curiosities <U+201C>We sat there like pieces of art in a showcase on display<U+201D> 
  | date = September 23, 2005
  | url = http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/50923/news/features/50923_01.html
  | accessdate =2009-10-06 }}
</ref> [[Abe Okpik]], [[Order of Canada|CM]], was instrumental in helping Inuit obtain [[Family name|surnames]] rather than [[disc numbers]] and [[Kiviaq]] (David Ward) won the legal right to use his single-word Inuktituk name.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Kiviaq versus Canada film by Zacharias Kunuk Produced by Katarina Soukup 
  | publisher = Isuma Distribution International Inc.
  | date = 2006
  | url =http://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&source=web&ct=res&cd=2&url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.isuma.ca%2FPress_kits%2FKiviaq_PressKit.pdf&ei=Tt3GSqrXOtDl8QavqvHhCA&usg=AFQjCNFkH4TnLRx4Fk_QXNZF2ly1otw8Dg
  | format = pdf
  | accessdate = 2009-10-03}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last =  Hanson
  | first = Ann Meekitjuk
  | title = Nunavut 99-What's In A Name? Names, as well as events, mark the road to Nunavut
  | publisher = Nunavut.com 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.nunavut.com/nunavut99/english/name.html
  | accessdate = 2009-10-03}}
</ref>

====M<U+00E9>tis====
{{Main|M<U+00E9>tis people (Canada)|Anglo-M<U+00E9>tis}}
[[File:Mixed blood Fur trader 1870.jpg|thumb|left|alt="Black and white photograph of a man of mixed blood designated as a fur trader"|upright|Mixed blood fur trader, c.1870]]
The M<U+00E9>tis are a people descended of marriages of Cree, Ojibway, Algonquin, [[Saulteaux]], [[Menominee]], Mi'kmaq, [[Maliseet]], and other First Nations to Europeans,<ref name=testt>{{cite web
  | title = What to Search: Topics-Canadian Genealogy Centre-Library and Archives Canada
  | work = Ethno-Cultural and Aboriginal Groups
  | publisher = Government of Canada
  | date = 2009-05-27
  | url = http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/genealogie/022-905.004-e.html
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref> mainly French.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Rinella
|first=Steven
|title=American Buffalo: In Search of A Lost Icon
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|date=2008
|publisher=Spiegel and Grau
|location=NY
|isbn=0385521685
}}
</ref> Their history dates to the mid-17th century.<ref name="First Nations Culture Areas Index"/>
The M<U+00E9>tis homeland consists of the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian provinces]] of [[British Columbia]], Alberta, [[Saskatchewan]], [[Manitoba]], [[Quebec]], [[New Brunswick]], [[Nova Scotia]], and [[Ontario]], as well as the [[Northwest Territories]] (NWT).<ref>{{cite book
|last=Howard
|first=James H
|title=The Plains-Ojibwa or Bungi: hunters and warriors of the Northern Prairies with special reference to the Turtle Mountain band
|format=Reprint by Lincoln, Nebraska: J. and L. Reprint Co. Reprints in Anthropology 7, 1977
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|edition=Museum Anthropology Papers 1
|date=1965
|publisher= [[University of South Dakota]]
|isbn=0160504007
}}
</ref>

Amongst nameable M<U+00E9>tis people are [[Tom Jackson (actor)|Tom Jackson]], [[TV|television]] actor, [[Tony Whitford]], [[Commissioner of the Northwest Territories]] and Louis Riel who led two resistance movements; the [[Red River Rebellion]] of 1869<U+2013>1870 and the [[North-West Rebellion]] of 1885 which ended in his [[Trial of Louis Riel|trial]].<ref name="LouisRielCE">{{cite web
 | last =The Canadian Encyclopedia
 | first =Historica Foundation of Canada.
 | title =Riel, Louis
 | year =2007
 | url =http://thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0006837
 | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | publisher =A database of materials held by the University of Saskatchewan Libraries and the University Archives
 | title =Louis Riel
 | url =http://library2.usask.ca/northwest/background/riel.htm
 | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last = Brown
  | first = Jane
  | title = Aboriginal Faces of Saskatchewan - Tom Jackson
  | work = Saskatchewan Sage - April 1998 - pg. 6
  | publisher = Saskatchewan Indian Cultural Centre 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.sicc.sk.ca/faces/mjackto.htm
  | accessdate =2009-10-05 }}
</ref><REF>{{cite web
  | title = Backgrounder  Biography of Anthony W.J. (Tony) Whitford - NWT Commissioner 
  | work = Indian and Northern Affairs Canada
  | publisher = 2005 News Releases 
  | date = 2008-10-28
  | url = http://www.ainc-inac.gc.ca/ai/mr/nr/j-a2005/02623bk-eng.asp
  | accessdate =2009-10-06 }}
</ref><ref name="martyr">{{cite web
 | last = Ricketts
 | first =Bruce
 | title =Louis Riel <U+2013> Martyr, hero or traitor?
 | year =1998<U+2013>2007
 | url =http://www.mysteriesofcanada.com/Canada/riel.htm
 | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }}</ref> 

The languages inhernelty M<U+00E9>tis are either [[M<U+00E9>tis French]] or a mixed language called [[Michif language|Michif]]. Michif, Mechif or M<U+00E9>tchif is a [[Pronunciation spelling|phonetic spelling]] of M<U+00E9>tif, a variant of M<U+00E9>tis.<ref name=mist>{{cite web|url=http://www.metisresourcecentre.mb.ca/language/language.htm|title=The Problem of Michif|work=By Peter Bakker-Metis Resource Centre (ISBN 0{{emdash}}19-509711-4)| accessdate =2009-10-05 }}</ref> The M<U+00E9>tis today predominantly speak [[Canadian English|English]], with [[Canadian French|French]] a strong second language, as well as numerous [[Indigenous languages of the Americas|Aboriginal tongues]]. A 19th Century community of the M<U+00E9>tis people, the [[Anglo-M<U+00E9>tis]], were referred to as Countryborn.  They were children of [[Rupert's Land]] fur trade typically of [[Orcadian]], [[Scottish people|Scottish]], or [[English people|English]] paternal descent and Aboriginal maternal descent.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Barkwell
|first=Lawrence J.
|coauthors=Leah Dorion, and Audreen Hourie
|title=Metis legacy Michif culture, heritage, and folkways
|volume=Metis legacy series, v. 2. 
|date=2006
|publisher= [[Gabriel Dumont]] Institute,
|location=Saskatoon, SK
|isbn=0920915809
}}
</ref>  Their first languages would have been Aboriginal ([[Cree language|Cree]], [[Saulteaux language|Saulteaux]], [[Assiniboine language|Assiniboine]], etc.) and [[English language|English]].  Their fathers spoke [[Canadian Gaelic|Gaelic]], thus leading to the development of an English dialect referred to as "[[Bungee language|Bungee]]".<ref>{{cite web |title=The Red River dialect|work=Blain,  Eleanor M. (1994)|publisher= Winnipeg: Wuerz Publishing|url=http://tceplus.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0001097 | accessdate =2009-10-15 }}</ref> 

There is debate over legally defining the term M<U+00E9>tis.<ref name=legal>{{cite web|url=http://www.metisnation.ca/who/definition.html|title=National Definition of M<U+00E9>tis |work=M<U+00E9>tis National Council| accessdate =2009-10-15 }}</ref>  Unlike First Nations people and Inuit, there is no distinction between [[Indian Register|status]] and non-status.<ref name=legal/>  S.35 of the Constitution Act, 1982 mentions the M<U+00E9>tis.  M<U+00E9>tis, their heritage and aboriginal ancestry have been absorbed and assimilated into their surrounding populations.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Barkwell
|first= Lawrence J.
|coauthors= Leah Dorion and Darren Prefontaine
|title=Metis Legacy: A Historiography and Annotated Bibliography
|date= 2001
|publisher= Pemmican Publications Inc. and Saskatoon: Gabriel Dumont Institute
|location=Winnipeg, MB
|isbn=1-894717-03-1
}}
</ref>

===Integration ===
{{Main|Canadian Indian residential school system|Indian Residential Schools Truth and Reconciliation Commission}}
From the late 18th century, European Canadians encouraged Aboriginals to assimilate into their own culture, referred to as "[[Culture of Canada|Canadian culture]]".<ref name = "RoyalCom-sg3">{{cite web | title = Indian and Northern Affairs Canada
  | work = Stage Three: Displacement and Assimilation
  | publisher = Government of Canada Web Archive-websites archived by Library and Archives Canada.
  | date =  2006-02-08 
  | url = http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/webarchives/20071124124236/http://www.ainc-inac.gc.ca/ch/rcap/sg/sgm6_e.html
  | accessdate = 2009-10-03}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | title = Report-Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples-Indian and Northern Affairs Canada
  | work = Volume 1, Part 1, Chapter 6 of the ''Report of the Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples''
  | publisher = Government of Canada Web Archive-websites archived by Library and Archives Canada [[Indian and Northern Affairs Canada]]
  | date = 2006-02-08 
  | url =http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/webarchives/20071115053257/http://www.ainc-inac.gc.ca/ch/rcap/sg/sgmm_e.html
  | accessdate =2009-10-03 }}
</ref>  These attempts reached a climax in the late 19th and early 20th centuries with forced integration. Due to laws and policies that encouraged or required Aboriginals to [[Cultural imperialism|assimilate]] into a [[Eurocentrism|Eurocentric]] society; Canada may be in violation of the [[United Nations]] [[Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide|Genocide Convention]] that Canada signed in 1949 and passed through parliament in 1952.<ref name="Restoule, Jean-Paul 2002">{{cite book
|last=Restoule
|first=Jean-Paul
|title=Aboriginal Identity: The Need for Historical and Contextual Perspectives
|accessdate=2009-10-28
|date=2002
|publisher=Pearson/Prentice Hall
|location=Toronto, ON
|pages=252 261
|chapter= Seeing Ourselves. John Macionis and Nijole v. Benokraitis and Bruce Ravelli
}}
</ref> The residential school system removed Aboriginal children from their homes for placement in Christian run schools has led scholars to believe that Canada can be tried in [[international court]] for [[genocide]].<ref name="Restoule, Jean-Paul 2002" /> [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] [[Stephen Harper]] issued an apology on behalf of the Canadian government and its citizens for the residential school system in 2008.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Benjoe
  | first = Kerry 
  | title = Group gathers for Harper's apology
  | publisher =  The Leader-Post
  | date =  June 12, 2008
  | url = http://www2.canada.com/reginaleaderpost/news/story.html?id=2e362bf9-0f5a-43c6-ab5e-81a276b4767c 
  | accessdate = 2009-10-02}}
</ref>

==Politics, law and legislation==
{{Main|The Canadian Crown and First Nations, Inuit and M<U+00E9>tis}}
===Treaties===
{{See|Numbered Treaties}}
[[Image:Medal-Viki.jpg|250px|thumb|left|alt="Photograph of the Indian Chiefs Medal, bearing the effigy of (Queen Victoria) on one side and the inscription Victoria Regina and a depiction of a man in European garb shaking hands with an Aboriginal in historic first nation clothing with the inscription Indian Treaty 187"|The Indian Chiefs Medal, presented to commemorate Treaties 3, 4, 5, 6 and 7, bearing the effigy of Queen [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Victoria]].]]
The [[The Canadian Crown and First Nations, Inuit and M<U+00E9>tis|Canadian Crown and Aboriginal peoples]] began [[Timeline of colonization of North America|interactions]] during the European colonialisation period.  [[Numbered treaties]], the  [[Indian Act]], the  [[Constitution Act, 1982|Constitution Act of 1982]] and case laws were established. Aboriginals construe these agreements as being between them and the [[Monarchy of Canada|Crown of Canada]] via the [[Indian Agent (Canada)|districts Indian Agent]], and not the [[Cabinet of Canada]].  The [[M<U+0101>ori]] interprets the [[Treaty of Waitangi]] in [[New Zealand]] similarly.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =  Mainville  
  | first = Sara
  | title = Lawsuits, treaty rights and the sacred balance
  | publisher = Toronto Star 
  | date = Jun 01, 2007
  | url = http://www.thestar.com/comment/article/220171
  | accessdate =2009-10-02}}
</ref> A series of eleven [[treaty|treaties]] were signed between Aboriginals in Canada and the reigning Monarch of Canada from 1871 to 1921.  The [[Government of Canada]] created the policy, commissioned the Treaty Commissioners and ratified the agreements.  These Treaties are agreements with the Government of Canada administered by [[Canadian Aboriginal law]] and overseen by the [[Minister of Indian Affairs and Northern Development (Canada)|Minister of Indian Affairs and Northern Development]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Treaty areas
  | work = Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat
  | publisher = Government of Canada
  | date = 2002-10-07
  | url = http://www.tbs-sct.gc.ca/dfrp-rbif/treaty-traite.asp?Language=EN
  | accessdate = 2009-10-02}}
</ref>

According to the proposed ''First Nations{{ndash}} Federal Crown Political Accord'' "cooperation will be a cornerstone for partnership between Canada and First Nations, wherein ''Canada'' is the short-form reference to Her Majesty the Queen in Right of Canada.<ref name=FN /> The [[Supreme Court of Canada|Supreme Court]] argued that treaties "served to reconcile pre-existing Aboriginal sovereignty with assumed Crown sovereignty, and to define Aboriginal rights".<ref name=FN>{{cite web
  | title = A First Nations-Federal Crown Political Accord on the Recognition and Implementation of First Nation Governments
  | work = Assembly of First Nations & Government of Canada
  | date = April 19, 2004
  | url = http://www.afn.ca/cmslib/general/PolAcc.pdf
  | format = pdf
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref> First Nations people interpreted agreements covered in [[treaty 8]] to last "as long as the sun shines, grass grows and rivers flow."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/aboriginals/treaty8.html|title=What is Treaty 8?|work=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation| accessdate =2009-10-05 }}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Indian Act and Bill C-31===
{{Main|Indian Act}}
[[File:Crombie1983.jpg|thumb|alt="Colour photograph of former Federal Minister for Indian Affairs and Northern Development, the Honorable David Crombie speaking to reporters on the floor of the 1983 Progressive Conservative leadership convention."|Former Federal Minister for Indian Affairs and Northern Development, the Honorable [[David Crombie]] was responsible for Bill C-31"<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Wuttunee
  | first = Deanna
  | title = Indian Act Amendments - Bill C-31
|work=Saskatchewan Indian
  | publisher = Saskatchewan Indian Cultural Centre
  | date = July 1985
  | url = http://www.sicc.sk.ca/saskindian/a85jul13.htm
|quote="Recognizing the right of Indian communities and bands to determine their own members marks a historic departure from a century of paternalism. It is also a milestone in the Government's desire to advance towards greater recognition of Indian self-government." 
| accessdate = 2009-10-19}}
</ref> ]]
The Indian Act is federal legislation that dates from 1876. There have been over twenty major changes made to the original Act since then, the last time being in 1951; amended in 1985 with [[Bill C-31]]. The Indian Act indicates how Reserves and Bands can operate and defines who is recognised as an "Indian".<ref name="laws">{{cite web
  | title = Update notice to the Justice Laws site
  | work = Indian Act. R.S., 1985, c. I-5 
  | publisher = Department of Justice Canada
  | date = 2009-09-29 
  | url = http://www.canlii.org/en/ca/laws/stat/rsc-1985-c-i-5/31743/rsc-1985-c-i-5.html#history
  | accessdate = 2009-10-02}}
</ref> 

In 1985, the Canadian Parliament passed Bill C-31, "An Act to Amend the Indian Act". Because of a Constitutional requirement, the Bill took affect as of April 17, 1985.<ref name="bill">{{cite web
  | title = First Nations, Bill C-31, Indian Act
  | work = Communications Branch
  | publisher = Department of Indian Affairs and Northern Development
  | url = http://www.johnco.com/nativel/bill_c31.html
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref>
* It ends discriminatory provisions of the Indian Act, especially those which discriminated against women.<ref name="bill"/>
* It changes the meaning of "status" and for the first time allows for limited reinstatement of Indians who were denied or lost status and/or Band membership in the past.<ref name="bill"/>
* It allows bands to define their own membership rules.<ref name="bill"/> 

Those people accepted into band membership under band rules may not be status Indians. C-31 clarified that various sections of the Indian Act would apply to band members. The sections under debate concern community life and land holdings. Sections pertaining to Indians (Aboriginals) as individuals (in this case, wills and taxation of personal property) were not included.<ref name="bill"/>
{{clear}}

===Royal Commission ===
{{Main|Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples}}

The [[Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples]] was a  [[Royal Commission]] undertaken by the Government of Canada in 1991 to address issues of the Aboriginal peoples of Canada.<ref name=royal/> It assessed past government policies toward Aboriginal people, such as [[Canadian Indian residential school system|residential schools]], and provided policy recommendations to the government.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = The Report of the Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples
  | work =  Mary C. Hurley, Law and Government Division, Jill Wherrett, Political and Social Affairs Division
  | publisher = Government of Canada (Library of Canada)
  | date = 4 October 1999
  | url =http://www.parl.gc.ca/information/library/PRBpubs/prb9924-e.htm
  | accessdate = 2009-10-06}}
</ref>The Commission issued its final report in November 1996. The five-volume, 4,000{{emdash}}page report covered a vast range of issues; its 440 recommendations called for sweeping changes to the interaction between Aboriginal, non-Aboriginal people and the governments in Canada.<ref name=royal>{{cite web|url=http://www.iog.ca/publications/healthrcap.pdf|format=pdf |title=Summary of the Final Report of The Royal Commission on Aboriginal |work=CTV Canada| accessdate = 2009-10-05}}</ref> The report "set out a 20{{emdash}}year agenda for change."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/information/library/PRBpubs/prb9924-e.htm|title=the Report of the Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples|work= Library of Parliament | accessdate = 2009-10-06}}</ref>

===Health policy===
{{Main|Indian Health Transfer Policy (Canada)}}
In 1995, the [[Government of Canada|federal government]] announced the Aboriginal Right to Self-Government Policy.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = I- Aboriginal Health &amp; Cultural Diversity Glossary, College of Nursing
  | publisher = [[University of Saskatchewan]]
  | date = 2003
  | url = http://www.usask.ca/nursing/aboriginalglossary/i.htm
  | accessdate = 2009-10-02}}
</ref> This policy recognises that First Nations and Inuit have the constitutional right to shape their own forms of government to suit their particular historical, cultural, political and economic circumstances. The [[Indian Health Transfer Policy (Canada)|Indian Health Transfer Policy]] provided a framework for the assumption of control of health services by Aboriginal peoples, and set forth a developmental approach to transfer centred on the concept of self-determination in health.<ref>{{cite book
  | last =Jacklin
  | first =Kristen 
  | coauthors = Wayne Warry
  |editor=Arachu Castro, Merrill Singer
  | title = Unhealthy health policy: a critical anthropological examination
  |chapter=14 Then Indian Health Transfer Policy in Canada: Toward Self-Determination or Cost Containment?
  |format=digitised online by Google books
  | publisher = Rowman Altamira
  |place=Oxford United Kingdom
  | date = 2004
  | pages = 215
  | url = http://books.google.ca/books?id=XWbF_tfYUuEC&pg=PA215&lpg=PA215&dq=Indian+Health+Transfer+Policy+in+canadal&source=bl&ots=SLL8UWqmnS&sig=swsX5CK_9WsknURGPZVkHNNnwPM&hl=en&ei=jhXBSt7ZNYya8AbXiq2lAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3#v=onepage&q=&f=false
  | isbn =0-7591-0510-3 
| accessdate =2009-10-06}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | title = Indian Health Policy 1979
  | work = About Health Canada > Branches & Agencies > First Nations & Inuit Health Branch
  | publisher = Health Canada
  | date = 2007-10-25
  | url = http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/ahc-asc/branch-dirgen/fnihb-dgspni/poli_1979-eng.php
  | format = php
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref>  Through this process, the decision to enter into transfer discussions with [[Health Canada]] rests with each community. Once involved in transfer, communities are able to take control of health programme responsibilities at a pace determined by their individual circumstances and health management capabilities.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Lemchuk-Favel
  | first = Laurel
  | title = Financing a First Nations and Inuit Integrated Health System A Discussion Document
  | work = Heallth Canada
  | publisher = 
  | date = February 22, 1999
  | url = http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/fniah-spnia/alt_formats/fnihb-dgspni/pdf/pubs/agree-accord/1999_finance_integr-eng.pdf
  | format = pdf
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref>  The [[National Aboriginal Health Organization]] (NAHO) incorporated in 2000, is an Aboriginal-designed and-controlled not-for-profit body in Canada that works to influence and advance the health and well-being of Aboriginal Peoples.<ref name="naho">{{cite web |url=http://www.naho.ca/english/|title=National Aboriginal Health Organization (NAHO) |work= Conference Board creates northern research centre|accessdate=2009-10-14}}</ref>

===Political organization===
{{Main|First Nations government (Canada)|M<U+00E9>tis National Council|Inuit Circumpolar Council}}
First Nations and Inuit organisations ranged in size from [[Band society|band societies]] of a few people to multi-nation confederacies like the Iroquois. First Nations leaders from across the country formed the [[Assembly of First Nations]], which began as the National Indian Brotherhood in 1968.<ref name="price"> {{cite book |last=Price |first=Richard |title=The Spirit of the Alberta Indian Treaties|publisher=	University of Alberta Press > the University of Michigan |date=1999|isbn=0888643276}}</ref>

Today's political organisations have resulted from interaction with European-style methods of government via the [[Federal Interlocutor for M<U+00E9>tis and Non-Status Indians]].  Aboriginal political organisations throughout Canada vary in political standing, viewpoints, and reasons for forming.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/aboriginal-heritage/020016-4010-e.html|title=Post-war Rise of Political Organizations|work=Library and Archives Canada| accessdate = 2009-10-06}}</ref> First Nations, M<U+00E9>tis and Inuit negotiate with the [[Politics of Canada|Canadian Government]] through [[Indian and Northern Affairs Canada]] in all affairs concerning land, entitlement, and rights.<ref name="price"/>  The First Nation groups that operate independently do not belong to these groups.<ref name="price"/>

==Culture==
{{See|Inuit culture|Notable Aboriginal people of Canada|National Aboriginal Day}}

There are distinctive Aboriginal cultures originating from all regions of Canada. [[Indian reserve]]s, established in [[Law of Canada|Canadian law]] by treaties such as [[Treaty 7]], are lands of First Nations recognised by non-indigenous governments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://74.125.93.132/search?q=cache%3ALX5RxMzdkJsJ%3Awww.uarctic.org%2Fmodule_12_tmDGm.pdf.file+Land+Claims%2C+Ownership%2C+and+Co-management&hl=en&gl=ca|title=Land Claims, Ownership, and Co-management|work=Developed by Ken Coates, Dean, College of Arts and Sciences, University of Saskatchewan and Greg Poelzer, Chair, Political Science Program, [[University of Northern British Columbia]]|format=pdf|accessdate = 2009-10-05}}</ref> Some reserves are within cities, such as the Opawikoscikan Reserve in [[Prince Albert, Saskatchewan]], [[Wendake, Quebec|Wendake]] in [[Quebec City]] or [[Stony Plain 135, Alberta|Stony Plain 135]] in the [[Edmonton Capital Region]]. There are more [[List of Indian reserves in Canada|reserves in Canada]] than there are First Nations, which were ceded multiple reserves by treaty.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.literacycommunity.com/grade3/firstnations/reserve.htm|title=The First Nations-Communities: Reserves|work=The Literacy Community| accessdate = 2009-10-05}}</ref>

[[Image:Tsuu Tsina parade.JPG|thumb|alt="Colour photograph of Tsuu T'ina children in traditional costume on horseback at a Stampede Parade in front of an audience"|[[Tsuu T'ina]] children at a parade]]
First Nations cultural areas depend upon their ancestors' primary [[Types of societies|lifeway]], or occupation, at the time of European contact. These culture areas correspond closely with [[geography of Canada|physical and ecological]] [[List of regions of Canada|regions of Canada]].<ref name="three">{{cite book
|editor=Goddard, Ives 
|others=W. C. Sturtevant
|title=Languages. Handbook of North American Indians 
|volume=17
|date=1996
|publisher= Smithsonian Institution
|location=[[Washington, D.C.|Washington, D. C.]]
|isbn=0-16-048774-9.
}} </ref>

The [[indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest Coast]] were centred around ocean and river fishing; in the interior of British Columbia, hunter-gatherer and river fishing. In both of these areas the salmon was of chief importance. For the people of the plains, bison hunting was the primary activity. In the [[taiga|subarctic forest]], other species such as the [[moose]] were more important. For peoples near the Great Lakes and [[Saint Lawrence River]], [[Shifting cultivation|shifting agriculture]] was practised, including the raising of [[maize]], [[bean]]s, and [[Squash (plant)|squash]].<ref name="three" /> While for the Inuit, hunting was the primary source of food with [[Pinniped|seals]] the primary component of their diet.<ref name="Searles">{{cite book
|last=Searles
|first=Edmund
|title=Food & Foodways: History & Culture of Human Nourishment 10 
|year=2002
|pages=55<U+2013>78
|chapter=Food and the Making of Modern Inuit Identities
}}
</ref> The [[Reindeer|caribou]], fish, other [[marine mammal]]s and to a lesser extent plants, berries and seaweed are part of the [[Inuit diet]].

Aboriginal people currently work in a variety of occupations and may live outside their ancestral homes. The traditional cultures of their ancestors, shaped by nature, still exert a strong influence on them, from spirituality to political attitudes.<ref name="three" />  National Aboriginal Day is a day of recognition of the cultures and contributions of the First Nations, Inuit and M<U+00E9>tis  peoples of Canada.  The day was first celebrated in 1996, after it was proclaimed that year, by then [[Governor General of Canada]] [[Rom<U+00E9>o LeBlanc]], to be celebrated on [[June 21]] annually.<ref name=history>{{cite web |url=http://dsp-psd.pwgsc.gc.ca/Collection/R32-179-2000E.pdf|title=National Aboriginal Day History|work=Indian and Northern Affairs Canada |format=pdf  | accessdate = 2009-10-18}}</ref> Most provincial jurisdictions do not recognise it as a [[Public holidays in Canada|statutory holiday]].<ref name=history/>

===Languages===
:''Main articles: [[Canadian Aboriginal syllabics]], [[Spoken languages of Canada#Aboriginal languages|First Nations Aboriginal languages]], [[Inuit language]], [[Eskimo-Aleut languages]] and [[Indigenous languages of the Americas]] ''
Today, there are over thirty different languages spoken by the indigenous peoples of North America, most of which are spoken uniquely in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/89-589-x/4067801-eng.htm|title=Aboriginal languages|work=Statistics Canada|accessdate = 2009-10-05}}</ref> Canada's indigenous languages are in decline.<ref name="online">{{Citation
  | last = Gordon
  | first = Raymond G Jr.
  | title = Ethnologue: Languages of the world 
  | place = Dallas, TX
  | publisher = SIL International
  | year = 2005
  | edition = 15
|format=Web Version online by SIL International,formerly known as the Summer Institute of Linguistics
  | url = http://www.ethnologue.com/web.asp
  | isbn =1-55671-159-X 
  | accessdate = 2009-10-06
}}
</ref> Two of Canada's territories give official status to native languages. In Nunavut, Inuktitut and [[Inuinnaqtun]] are official languages alongside the national languages of English and French, and Inuktitut is a common vehicular language in territorial government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.langcom.nu.ca/languages/en_index.html|work=Office of the Languages Commissioner of Nunavut|title=Nunavut's Languages | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}</ref>In the NWT, the ''Official Languages Act'' declares that there are eleven different languages: [[Dene Suline language|Chipewyan]], Cree, English, French, [[Gwich<U+2019>in language|Gwich<U+2019>in]], Inuinnaqtun, [[Inuktitut]], [[Inuvialuktun]], [[Slavey language|North Slavey]], [[Slavey language|South Slavey]] and [[Dogrib language|T<U+0142><U+012F>ch<U+01EB>]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Official Languages Act
  | work =  Legislation
Division, Department of Justice
  | date = 1988
  | url = http://www.justice.gov.nt.ca/PDF/ACTS/Official_Languages.pdf 
  | format =pdf 
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref> Besides English and French, these languages are not vehicular in government; official status entitles citizens to receive services in them on request and to deal with the government in them.<ref name="online" />

